Apply hierarchical clustering

Agnes

hc_single <- agnes(nutrition, method = "single")
hc_complete <- agnes(nutrition, method = "complete")
hc_average <- agnes(nutrition, method = "average")
hc_ward <- agnes(nutrition, method = "ward")

print(hc_single$ac)
## [1] 0.6878427
print(hc_complete$ac)
## [1] 0.8851994
print(hc_average$ac)
## [1] 0.8288271
print(hc_ward$ac) # Best defined clustering (.92)
## [1] 0.9175011

Plot Ward dendrogram

pltree(hc_ward, cex = 0.8, hang = -1, main = "Cereal nutrition dendrogram - Agnes Ward method")

How many clusters would you choose?

I want to cut my Ward dendrogram at a height of 6, achieving six clusters. I tried four and five clusters, but six divides a very large cluster into two more insightful clusters, one of which appears (at first glance) to be cereals typically known as high sugar but otherwise low nutritional value. Id want to explore this further.

d <- dist(nutrition, method = "euclidean") 
ward <- hclust(d, method = "ward.D2") # base r (stats) ward.D2
plot(ward, cex = .8, hang = -1)
rect.hclust(ward, k = 6, border = 1:6)

Validate Clusters

Mean nutritional values by cluster

While analyzing the mean nutritional values by cluster, I realized that I inadvertently excluded potassium and vitamins from the nutrition dataframe that I used for clustering. Im too far in now to go back and correct for that.

Cluster 1 = High satiety cereals (low calorie, high protein, high fiber) Cluster 2 = Granola (high fat, high calorie) Cluster 3 = Plain cereal (low sugar) Cluster 4 = Sugary cereal (low protein, low fiber, high sugar) Cluster 5 = Starchy cereal (high sodium, high carbohydrates, low fiber, low sugar) Cluster 6 = Natural cereal (low sodium, low sugar)

cluster_labels <- cutree(ward, k=6) # assign cluster labels
aggregate(nutrition, by = list(cluster = cluster_labels), FUN = mean) # means of nutrition features by cluster
